'''Relativity Space''', is a private American [[aerospace manufacturer]] company headquartered in [[Los Angeles, California]]. It was founded in 2015 by Tim Ellis and Jordan Noone. <ref name="ARS-20180321">{{cite web |author=Eric Berger |title=Relativity Space reveals its ambitions with big NASA deal |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2018/03/relativity-space-reveals-its-ambitions-with-big-nasa-deal/ |date=March 21, 2018 |publisher=Ars Technica |accessdate=March 25, 2018 }}</ref>
Relativity Space was founded on the idea that [[Blue Origin]] and [[SpaceX]] weren't doing enough to use [[3D printing]] as part of rocket manufacturing. Relativity plans to 3D print and entire [[launch vehicle]]. The extensive use of 3D printing has allowed the company to iterate designs quickly, use less tooling and human labor. In order to 3D print large objects Relativity has created a system named Stargate which it claims is the worlds largest 3d printer of metals.<ref name="spacenews-201712015">{{cite web |author=Jeff Foust |title=Relativity Space aims to 3D print entire launch vehicles |url=http://spacenews.com/relativity-space-aims-to-3d-print-entire-launch-vehicles/ |date=December 5, 2017 |publisher=Space News |accessdate=March 25, 2018 }}</ref> In March of 2018 Relativity Space secured a 20 year partnership with NASA Stennis Space Center. This partnership will allow Relativity to continue to test engine components and eventually completed [[Aeon rocket engine]]s. <ref name=ARS-20180321/>
